  "opinion": "As a plumber in Rome with no formal education beyond what my parents taught me, I’ve never really heard the term 'stereotype threat' in my daily work. But I’m curious about it because it’s something people talk about in schools and universities. Stereotype threat is when someone feels pressure because of a stereotype about their group—like thinking women aren’t good at math or that people from my background don’t belong in tech. For me, as a man who works with hands and tools, I’ve never felt that pressure myself. But I know from my kids’ school that some girls might feel shy about math if they think it’s not for them. In my community, we don’t have a lot of STEM roles, so maybe stereotype threat is real for others. Should we address it? Absolutely. In Rome, where I’ve seen kids from all walks of life playing football and doing yoga together, we can help them see that science isn’t just for the smart ones. I’d say the best way is by making STEM fun and accessible—like showing kids how plumbing connects to engineering or how fixing a leak is a real-life problem-solving job. If we do this, stereotype threat fades because kids see themselves in the work. I’m not an expert, but my curiosity and experience with my kids’ world make me think we can change this without formal education. It’s about building confidence, not labels.",
